WIRED put up [a mesmerizing gallery](http://www.wired.com/wiredscience/2013/10/nikon-small-world-2013/) of microscopy photos created for the [Nikon Small World competition](http://www.nikonsmallworld.com/).

There are many brilliant shots to thumb through: some showing the complexity of mouse vertebra, the regularity of a turtle retina, and the delicate mesh of a developing mouse embryo's nervous system.

The image above is a chameleon embryo stained for bone (red) and cartilage (blue) taken by Dorit Hockman, a PhD student at the University of Cambridge, who submitted [photos of three embryonic bats](http://www.nikonsmallworld.com/galleries/entry/2012-photomicrography-competition/20) to the 2012 competition.
